  <p>
    Arizona's climate makes it one of the best states for year-round cycling. It also makes it one of the most dangerous. Wide, high-speed roads designed primarily for vehicles. Limited bike infrastructure in many communities. Drivers who don't expect cyclists or don't know how to share the road. When a car hits a bicycle, the cyclist absorbs the full impact with nothing but clothing and maybe a helmet between them and the pavement.
  </p>

  <h2>The Three-Foot Rule</h2>

  <p>
    Arizona law requires drivers to maintain at least three feet of clearance when passing a bicycle. This isn't a suggestion. It's the law. Violations are citable offenses, and in the context of a crash case, a three-foot violation is strong evidence of negligence.
  </p>

  <p>
    Despite the law, close passes happen constantly. Drivers misjudge distances, get impatient, or simply don't look. On roads without bike lanes, the conflict is even worse. Cyclists have a legal right to use the travel lane, but exercising that right puts them in close proximity to vehicles traveling 15 to 40 mph faster.
  </p>

  <h2>Bike Lane Myths</h2>

  <p>
    Many drivers believe cyclists must ride in bike lanes. That's not true. Arizona law permits cyclists to use bike lanes where they exist, but doesn't require it. Cyclists can and should leave the bike lane when it's unsafe: to avoid debris, to make left turns, to pass slower cyclists, or when the lane is too narrow.
  </p>

  <p>
    Some of the most dangerous cycling situations happen within bike lanes. Doors opening from parked cars. Right-turning vehicles cutting across the lane. Debris that accumulates because bike lanes don't get swept as often as travel lanes. Cyclists have to constantly make judgment calls about whether the bike lane or the travel lane is safer.
  </p>

  <h2>West Valley Cycling Conditions</h2>

  <p>
    Buckeye, Goodyear, and the wider West Valley have seen rapid growth. Cycling infrastructure hasn't kept pace. Many arterial roads lack bike lanes entirely. Shoulders are narrow or nonexistent. Intersections along routes like Yuma Road, Estrella Parkway, and Litchfield Road see regular conflicts between cyclists and vehicles.
  </p>

  <p>
    Construction zones add another layer of danger. Lane shifts, gravel, and temporary surfaces that a car handles easily can send a cyclist down. When road conditions or construction projects cause a crash, the responsible entity, whether a government agency or a construction company, may be liable.
  </p>

  <h2>Common Crash Types</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>Right hook:</strong> a vehicle turns right across a cyclist's path, often at an intersection or driveway. The driver either didn't see the cyclist or misjudged the closing speed.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Left cross:</strong> an oncoming vehicle turns left in front of a cyclist. This is one of the most dangerous crash types because the closing speed is high.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Dooring:</strong> a driver or passenger opens a car door into the path of a cyclist. These crashes happen quickly and the cyclist has almost no time to react.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Rear-end:</strong> a driver hits a cyclist from behind. Often caused by distracted driving, speeding, or failure to maintain the three-foot buffer.
  </p>

  <h2>Injuries and Long-Term Impact</h2>

  <p>
    Bicycle crash injuries tend to be severe relative to the speed of impact. Road rash that covers large areas of skin. Broken collarbones, wrists, and hips. Traumatic brain injuries, even with helmets. Spinal injuries. Facial fractures. Many cyclists are unable to work for weeks or months after a serious crash.
  </p>

  <p>
    The bike itself often needs to be replaced. High-end road bikes, gravel bikes, and e-bikes can cost thousands of dollars. We include property damage in every claim alongside medical expenses, lost wages, and pain and suffering.
  </p>

